She asks us, as archival workers and
-----
chunk #230 , size:40
practitioners, to build better listening
-----
chunk #231 , size:47
practices that, rather than being “starved from
-----
chunk #232 , size:41
relations,” are in full relationship with
-----
chunk #233 , size:40
record-creating communities.  Relational
-----
chunk #234 , size:39
responsibility is also surfaced through
-----
chunk #235 , size:45
discussion of records stewardship by Lomas et
-----
chunk #236 , size:42
al., Brilmyer, and Payne, who advocate for
-----
chunk #237 , size:47
reciprocal and community-based models of caring
-----
chunk #238 , size:49
for records and making them accessible over time.
-----
chunk #239 , size:45
In exploring the recordkeeping practices that
-----
chunk #240 , size:44
bind families to the memories of disappeared
-----
chunk #241 , size:38
relatives, Aton and Qvortrup & Giraldo
-----
chunk #242 , size:49
demonstrate a form of records stewardship that is
-----
chunk #243 , size:44
rooted in justice, responsibility, and love.
-----
chunk #244 , size:42
The relational archival forces that emerge
-----
chunk #245 , size:42
through this special issue demonstrate the
-----
chunk #246 , size:47
wide-ranging and at times interrelated forms of
-----
chunk #247 , size:41
care and feeling that are foundational to
-----
chunk #248 , size:48
building and maintaining archival relationships.
-----
chunk #249 , size:46
The authors do not offer a singular or unified
-----
chunk #250 , size:46
approach to archival relational responsibility
-----
chunk #251 , size:47
but, rather, demonstrate archival relationality
-----
chunk #252 , size:49
as situated, localized, and essential to building
-----
chunk #253 , size:27
archival meaning over time.
-----
chunk #254 , size:48
# Centring Emotions, Desires, and Experiences of
-----
chunk #255 , size:27
Communities and Individuals
-----
chunk #256 , size:49
A third key theme that emerges from the different
-----
chunk #257 , size:44
articles included in this special issue is a
-----
chunk #258 , size:47
focus on the emotions, desires, and experiences
-----
chunk #259 , size:48
of communities and individuals who are connected
-----
chunk #260 , size:47
to – or in relationship with – records and each
-----
chunk #261 , size:47
other. In different ways, the articles validate
-----
chunk #262 , size:45
the idea that emotions and feelings should be
-----
chunk #263 , size:41
central concerns for archivists, archival
-----
chunk #264 , size:49
policy-makers, and institutions. Individually and
-----
chunk #265 , size:41
collectively, the articles illustrate the
-----
chunk #266 , size:41
important relationships between emotions,
-----
chunk #267 , size:49
power(lessness), and possibility and, especially,
-----
chunk #268 , size:48
the power of emotion to disrupt power and invoke
-----
chunk #269 , size:42
possibility. Emotions, feelings, and lived
-----
chunk #270 , size:42
experiences are also shown to be important
-----
chunk #271 , size:41
elements of the work involved in righting
-----
chunk #272 , size:49
archival wrongs. In contexts in which communities
-----
chunk #273 , size:45
or phenomena are new to the realm of archival
-----
chunk #274 , size:49
work, scholars often use emotional narratives and
-----
chunk #275 , size:48
impacts to assert the validity of their work and
-----
chunk #276 , size:46
the importance of training the archival eye on
-----
chunk #277 , size:47
the communities in question. In these instances
-----
chunk #278 , size:46
(Brilmyer; Aton; Qvortrup and Giraldo), we see
-----
chunk #279 , size:49
how emotion is intricately tied to experiences of
-----
chunk #280 , size:48
powerlessness, and we are encouraged to consider
-----
chunk #281 , size:48
the depth of the contributions these experiences
-----
chunk #282 , size:49
could make to archival work and scholarship. Some
-----
chunk #283 , size:46
contributors extend extant bodies of work that
-----
chunk #284 , size:42
assert the important relationships between
-----
chunk #285 , size:47
communities and particular bodies of records by
-----
chunk #286 , size:46
exploring the possible ways in which affective
-----
chunk #287 , size:48
experiences might successfully be represented in
-----
chunk #288 , size:49
archival practice (Lomas et al.; Laurent, O’Neil,
-----
chunk #289 , size:47
and Wright; Payne; Christen). In the context of
-----
chunk #290 , size:43
critically reflexive scholarship (Guerrero;
-----
chunk #291 , size:38
Malek), archivists’ personal emotional
-----
chunk #292 , size:48
experiences and the relational elements of their
-----
chunk #293 , size:47
work become sites of possibility, where emotion
-----
chunk #294 , size:45
can fuel imaginings about the future of work.
-----
chunk #295 , size:47
Although centring a different source of emotion
-----
chunk #296 , size:46
from the other strategies outlined above, this
-----
chunk #297 , size:45
work offers similar contributions in centring
-----
chunk #298 , size:42
emotion as a site for disciplinary growth.
-----
chunk #299 , size:47
Ultimately, the articles in this collection and
-----
chunk #300 , size:48
the methodologies their authors employ highlight
-----
chunk #301 , size:40
the centrality of emotion to the work of
-----
chunk #302 , size:40
person-centred archival scholarship. The
-----
chunk #303 , size:47
validation and respectful harnessing of emotion
-----
chunk #304 , size:46
are key features of the ongoing work to centre
-----
chunk #305 , size:42
the person in archival studies and theory.
-----
chunk #306 , size:14
# The Articles
-----
chunk #307 , size:48
The authors who contribute to this special issue
-----
chunk #308 , size:49
do so from a range of perspectives and positions.
-----
chunk #309 , size:48
They include archival scholars, both established
-----
chunk #310 , size:48
and emerging, as well as professional archivists
-----
chunk #311 , size:49
with different levels of experience. The articles
-----
chunk #312 , size:48
they contribute demonstrate that the term person
-----
chunk #313 , size:40
centred can be applied across a range of
-----
chunk #314 , size:47
perspectives and positions, too; it can be used
-----
chunk #315 , size:43
to describe an archival function, a type of
-----
chunk #316 , size:46
archives (e.g., personal collections), a broad
-----
chunk #317 , size:46
methodological approach, or a moral or ethical
-----
chunk #318 , size:7
stance.
-----
chunk #319 , size:46
The articles can be grouped in different ways;
-----
chunk #320 , size:46
their approaches to what it means to be person
-----
chunk #321 , size:47
centred, to identifying past and current harms,
-----
chunk #322 , size:48
and to reimagining new ways to practice archives
-----
chunk #323 , size:49
overlap and interweave. In our structuring of the
-----
chunk #324 , size:41
issue, we have decided to present them as
-----
chunk #325 , size:46
follows. First, there is a cluster of articles
-----
chunk #326 , size:43
that, while not reducible to frameworks and
-----
chunk #327 , size:47
models, each suggests frameworks for repair and
-----
chunk #328 , size:49
reimagining: Kim Christen lays down a path toward
-----
chunk #329 , size:44
reparative recordkeeping based in Indigenous
-----
chunk #330 , size:49
models of kinship; Elizabeth Lomas et al. provide
-----
chunk #331 , size:41
a structured framework for person-centred
-----
chunk #332 , size:49
recordkeeping in out-of-home child-care contexts;
-----
chunk #333 , size:45
and Nicola Laurent, Cate O’Neill, and Kirsten
-----
chunk #334 , size:48
Wright describe an explicitly person-centred and
-----
chunk #335 , size:43
trauma-informed approach to arrangement and
-----
chunk #336 , size:12
description.
-----
chunk #337 , size:49
Each article in the next cluster introduces a new
-----
chunk #338 , size:46
concept to archival discourse. Gracen Brilmyer
-----
chunk #339 , size:38
asks readers to consider how “archival
-----
chunk #340 , size:47
in/accessibility” is “emotionally expensive,” a
-----
chunk #341 , size:48
term that expresses how the affective impacts of
-----
chunk #342 , size:45
inaccessibility accumulate and compound – not
-----
chunk #343 , size:41
only through the experience of navigating
-----
chunk #344 , size:49
inaccessible physical spaces but also through the
-----
chunk #345 , size:44
access policies of archival repositories and
-----
chunk #346 , size:45
their expectations about how archival work is
-----
chunk #347 , size:42
carried out. Krystal Payne brings together
-----
chunk #348 , size:46
literature on harm reduction and on Indigenous
-----
chunk #349 , size:45
relationality and resurgence to propose a new
-----
chunk #350 , size:47
concept of “archival harm reduction,” which she
-----
chunk #351 , size:45
suggests could guide settler archivists’ work
-----
chunk #352 , size:37
toward reparative, participatory, and
-----
chunk #353 , size:47
community-based praxis. In the third article in
-----
chunk #354 , size:46
this cluster, Emily Guerrero explores the ways
-----
chunk #355 , size:48
that gossip, often maligned as frivolous, can be
-----
chunk #356 , size:47
employed as a “tactic of care” across different
-----
chunk #357 , size:46
aspects of archival work, opening up space for
-----
chunk #358 , size:43
prioritizing new kinds of relationships and
-----
chunk #359 , size:11
narratives.
-----
chunk #360 , size:42
In the cluster that closes the issue, each
-----
chunk #361 , size:43
article centres care for particular people.
-----
chunk #362 , size:47
Articles by Henria Aton and by Natalia Bermúdez
-----
chunk #363 , size:47
Qvortrup and Marta Lucía Giraldo offer analyses
-----
chunk #364 , size:49
of archives created by the families of people who
-----
chunk #365 , size:49
have been forcibly disappeared, calling attention
-----
chunk #366 , size:44
to the absent presence of their creators and
-----
chunk #367 , size:47
connecting the creation of personal archives to
-----
chunk #368 , size:48
personal grief work, liberatory memory work, and
-----
chunk #369 , size:45
collective political action. In each of these
-----
chunk #370 , size:49
articles, an archival practice that is centred on
-----
chunk #371 , size:45
a very particular person, a disappeared loved
-----
chunk #372 , size:46
one, is shown to have impacts that reverberate
-----
chunk #373 , size:46
beyond the personal, connecting personal grief
-----
chunk #374 , size:45
and love to the pursuit of political justice.
-----
chunk #375 , size:41
Drawing on recent discussions in archival
-----
chunk #376 , size:44
literature about grief and love, and weaving
-----
chunk #377 , size:48
together insights pulled from queer and feminist
-----
chunk #378 , size:44
theory, anti-colonial methodologies, and new
-----
chunk #379 , size:49
materialism, Claire Malek likewise focuses on the
-----
chunk #380 , size:48
archives of an individual in her analysis of her
-----
chunk #381 , size:47
work with the Lilian Bland Fonds. Malek ponders
-----
chunk #382 , size:49
what it can mean to “do right by” an individual’s
-----
chunk #383 , size:49
archives; her own experience as an archivist; and
-----
chunk #384 , size:44
the ways the archives, their creator(s), and
-----
chunk #385 , size:49
archivists are in relationship, developing in the
-----
chunk #386 , size:45
process what she calls a “radical somatics of
-----
chunk #387 , size:24
critical archival love.”
-----
chunk #388 , size:46
It is clear, even in this brief description of
-----
chunk #389 , size:43
the articles, that these “clusters” are not
-----
chunk #390 , size:49
mutually exclusive. For example, Malek introduces
-----
chunk #391 , size:45
a new concept, “somatics of critical archival
-----
chunk #392 , size:43
love,” while Payne suggests a framework for
-----
chunk #393 , size:42
archival harm reduction. The articles work
-----
chunk #394 , size:49
together in different combinations to suggest new
-----
chunk #395 , size:47
ways of centring the person at the heart of the
-----
chunk #396 , size:45
record, and we hope that the ordering we have
-----
chunk #397 , size:49
chosen – which begins with kinship (Christen) and
-----
chunk #398 , size:44
ends with love (Malek) – provides an initial
-----
chunk #399 , size:29
pathway for your exploration.
-----
chunk #400 , size:21
# Remaining Questions
-----
chunk #401 , size:47
As we conclude this short introduction, we wish
-----
chunk #402 , size:45
to acknowledge some aspects of person-centred
-----
chunk #403 , size:44
archival theory and praxis that require more
-----
chunk #404 , size:45
attention than this issue provides. First, it
-----
chunk #405 , size:48
matters, often urgently, that we continue to ask
-----
chunk #406 , size:49
who is envisioned as the “person” at the heart of
-----
chunk #407 , size:49
person-centred approaches. Who, precisely, are we
-----
chunk #408 , size:47
centring? When, and why? Across the articles in
-----
chunk #409 , size:45
this issue, there is a common call to refocus
-----
chunk #410 , size:42
archival theories and methods so that they
-----
chunk #411 , size:45
acknowledge and provide care not only for the
-----
chunk #412 , size:44
records archivists preserve but also for the
-----
chunk #413 , size:48
people who create, keep, use, are documented in,
-----
chunk #414 , size:48
and steward those records. Particular importance
-----
chunk #415 , size:49
is placed, throughout the contributions, on those
-----
chunk #416 , size:49
persons who have traditionally had less agency in
-----
chunk #417 , size:43
recordkeeping or who have been historically
-----
chunk #418 , size:44
marginalized in recordkeeping discourses and
-----
chunk #419 , size:48
practices, including records subjects and others
-----
chunk #420 , size:47
impacted by decisions about how to describe and
-----
chunk #421 , size:46
provide access to records. As discussed above,
-----
chunk #422 , size:44
the impacts of recordkeeping have often been
-----
chunk #423 , size:48
harmful – especially for many Indigenous, Black,
-----
chunk #424 , size:48
brown, queer, and disabled communities, for whom
-----
chunk #425 , size:47
the archive has acted as a site of violence and
-----
chunk #426 , size:45
erasure. Despite the focus in the articles in
-----
chunk #427 , size:49
this issue (and beyond it) on the experiences and
-----
chunk #428 , size:47
needs of people who have been excluded from and
-----
chunk #429 , size:43
impacted by decisions archivists make about
-----
chunk #430 , size:49
records, there remains a need to think critically
-----
chunk #431 , size:47
about who is included – or not – in ideas about
-----
chunk #432 , size:46
person-centred theory and practices. Brilmyer,
-----
chunk #433 , size:39
for example, shows us how some people’s
-----
chunk #434 , size:47
personhood is called into question in archives,
-----
chunk #435 , size:49
through the design of spaces and through policies
-----
chunk #436 , size:47
and procedures that disregard disabled peoples’
-----
chunk #437 , size:45
lived experiences. In its illumination of the
-----
chunk #438 , size:37
many ways disabled people’s needs are
-----
chunk #439 , size:47
deprioritized in archival spaces and practices,
-----
chunk #440 , size:47
their article is a clear call to consider which
-----
chunk #441 , size:49
people are centred in the development of archival
-----
chunk #442 , size:25
theory and methodologies.
-----
chunk #443 , size:47
We also need to consider more fully a question,
-----
chunk #444 , size:47
raised in both Christen’s and Malek’s articles,
-----
chunk #445 , size:43
about “other-than-human beings.” Drawing on
-----
chunk #446 , size:48
perspectives on personhood in the work of Daniel
-----
chunk #447 , size:49
Heath Justice, Rosi Braidotti, and Donna Haraway,
-----
chunk #448 , size:45
Malek ponders how archivists can “do right by
-----
chunk #449 , size:49
[. . .] persons in their non-human forms.” In the
-----
chunk #450 , size:40
context of the Lilian Bland Fonds, these
-----
chunk #451 , size:49
non-human persons include animals as well as “the
-----
chunk #452 , size:45
lands and waters present in the fonds.” Malek
-----
chunk #453 , size:47
argues that, as archivists working with records
-----
chunk #454 , size:39
documenting or benefiting from resource
-----
chunk #455 , size:47
extraction and colonialism on lands stolen from
-----
chunk #456 , size:47
Indigenous Peoples in a time of climate crisis,
-----
chunk #457 , size:49
it is crucial that we engage with questions about
-----
chunk #458 , size:48
“what it means to treat the records of a forest,
-----
chunk #459 , size:47
a river, or an underground space as the records
-----
chunk #460 , size:42
of persons.” Christen also reflects on the
-----
chunk #461 , size:47
personhood of “non-humans,” including “material
-----
chunk #462 , size:42
belongings, words uttered or sung, and/ or
-----
chunk #463 , size:49
physical places on the lands.” Josiah, one of her
-----
chunk #464 , size:48
interlocutors, describes cultural belongings and
-----
chunk #465 , size:42
collections as relations and as kin; here,
-----
chunk #466 , size:42
person-centred approaches to recordkeeping
-----
chunk #467 , size:34
contend with the record as person.
-----
chunk #468 , size:45
There are other areas this special issue only
-----
chunk #469 , size:39
gestures toward. In order to be able to
-----
chunk #470 , size:42
conceptualize and actualize person-centred
-----
chunk #471 , size:46
archival theory and praxis, it is important to
-----
chunk #472 , size:44
consider all aspects of archival systems and
-----
chunk #473 , size:49
processes. While certain aspects of archival work
-----
chunk #474 , size:48
are addressed in articles in this special issue,
-----
chunk #475 , size:44
some archival functions are not represented;
-----
chunk #476 , size:41
these include archival appraisal, digital
-----
chunk #477 , size:47
preservation, and the design of digital systems
-----
chunk #478 , size:43
and interfaces. And although several of the
-----
chunk #479 , size:49
articles here engage with archival practices that
-----
chunk #480 , size:45
are anti-racist in intention and nature, this
-----
chunk #481 , size:49
issue does not include an article that makes this
-----
chunk #482 , size:38
area of scholarship its primary focus.
-----
chunk #483 , size:46
Recognizing this gap, we want to highlight the
-----
chunk #484 , size:44
work of other recent special issues that are
-----
chunk #485 , size:46
explicitly anti-racist in their focus and that
-----
chunk #486 , size:41
surface different modes of person-centred
-----
chunk #487 , size:45
archival work and practice; these include the
-----
chunk #488 , size:44
special issues of The Black Scholar on Black
-----
chunk #489 , size:49
archival practice, edited by Tonia Sutherland and
-----
chunk #490 , size:49
Zakiya Collier, and the forthcoming special issue
-----
chunk #491 , size:46
of Journal of Critical Library and Information
-----
chunk #492 , size:49
Studies on “the mattering of Black lives,” edited
-----
chunk #493 , size:49
by Michelle Caswell, Safiya Umoja Noble, Sarah T.
-----
chunk #494 , size:30
Roberts, and Tonia Sutherland.
-----
chunk #495 , size:15
# An Invitation
-----
chunk #496 , size:39
We close this introduction with a final
-----
chunk #497 , size:49
reflection on what we hope this special issue can
-----
chunk #498 , size:41
offer the evolving lens of person-centred
-----
chunk #499 , size:47
archival theory and praxis. While we provide no
-----
chunk #500 , size:41
firm or final definitions, approaches, or
-----
chunk #501 , size:41
guidelines, we believe there is power and
-----
chunk #502 , size:49
potential in bringing together ideas to try to do
-----
chunk #503 , size:48
this work. In a field with practical application
-----
chunk #504 , size:44
like archival studies, naming and defining a
-----
chunk #505 , size:47
phenomenon or practice permits us to prioritize
-----
chunk #506 , size:48
certain actions and types of decision-making. It
-----
chunk #507 , size:48
allows us to create policies and procedures that
-----
chunk #508 , size:44
embed and enact a person-centred approach to
-----
chunk #509 , size:44
archival stewardship that is oriented toward
-----
chunk #510 , size:42
addressing past harms, ameliorating unjust
-----
chunk #511 , size:42
practices, and envisioning more liberatory
-----
chunk #512 , size:46
archival futures. The authors included in this
-----
chunk #513 , size:49
special issue – and the theorists, practitioners,
-----
chunk #514 , size:48
archival users, and records subjects they evoke,
-----
chunk #515 , size:42
cite, and centre – provide us with salient
-----
chunk #516 , size:43
examples of how we address, ameliorate, and
-----
chunk #517 , size:43
envision. Importantly, they all figure “the
-----
chunk #518 , size:44
archive” as a set of relations that expands,
-----
chunk #519 , size:49
shifts, and changes over time as different actors
-----
chunk #520 , size:49
move in and out of view. Existing at the heart of
-----
chunk #521 , size:49
all archival relations, of course, are the people
-----
chunk #522 , size:41
who create records, use records, care for
-----
chunk #523 , size:49
records, and appear in the stories and narratives
-----
chunk #524 , size:43
we tell about records and their legacies. A
-----
chunk #525 , size:48
person-centred approach to archival practice and
-----
chunk #526 , size:48
theory recognizes this. It invites each of us in
-----
chunk #527 , size:49
as part of the ever-growing web of relations that
-----
chunk #528 , size:48
sustain archives and imbue them with meaning. We
-----
chunk #529 , size:45
hope that the themes emerging from this issue
-----
chunk #530 , size:47
provide an opening for building and elaborating
-----
chunk #531 , size:48
the frameworks of archival care, responsibility,
-----
chunk #532 , size:48
stewardship, and reflexivity we need to continue
-----
chunk #533 , size:45
creating and enacting person-centred archival
-----
chunk #534 , size:47
theory and practices. Starting with kin, ending
-----
chunk #535 , size:48
with love, and filled throughout with care, this
-----
chunk #536 , size:48
issue invites you to reflect on the theories and
-----
chunk #537 , size:43
approaches that guide your own research and
-----
chunk #538 , size:9
practice.
-----
chunk #539 , size:44
